  "Often the difference between competence and mastery is in the consistent pursuit of progress. Consider this post that pursuit.": "",
  "To truly master React, which is the ultimate goal of this course, you need the understanding to recognize different approaches for solving the same problem, and the knowledge to choose the optimal solution.": "",
  "There's no problem you'll find in this post that you don't already have the tools to solve. However, like using a butter knife to cut a steak, some tools are better (or worse) than others in specific situations.": "",
  "If you remember back to those posts, we established a list of rules we could follow for effectively managing side effects in React.": "",
  "Rule #0": "",
  "When a component renders, it should do so without running into any side effects": "",
  "Rule #1": "",
  "If a side effect is triggered by an event, put that side effect in an event handler": "",
  "Rule #2": "",
  "If a side effect is synchronizing your component with some outside system, put that side effect inside useEffect": "",
  "Now before you get too overwhelmed, know that these 3 rules cover ~95% of use cases you'll see when dealing with side effects in React. Unfortunately, that ~5% still exists and it stands in the way of your mastery.": "",
